{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596231"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:11:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:11:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15400"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15400"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.27,0.14,0.18,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8091"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15400"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20725"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EColonic diverticulosis is a common condition and can be found in about 70% of individuals over the age of 80 in western communities. (Image) For reasons that are not fully understood, this condition is rapidly becoming more prevalent in younger age groups. This does raise concern as some 10 - 25% of those with diverticular disease will experience an episode of acute diverticulitis (ie inflammation of diverticula in the colon). Of these, 15% will have some sort of complication which could have serious consequences.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common complication of diverticulitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bleeding","Perforation and peritonitis","Abscess formation","Fistula development","Bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMost patients who experience an episode of acute diverticulitis will have lower left sided abdominal pain, with possible bloating and change in bowel habit, and symptoms that will resolve over a few days with minimal need for any form of active intervention. However, when complications do occur, they are usually related to \u003Cstrong\u003Eabscess formation\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the result of a localised perforation and could be followed by free \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforation and peritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Efistula formation\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe predominant left-sided abdominal pain that occurs in diverticulitis is because the common site for diverticula formation is the sigmoid colon. When \u003Cstrong\u003Ebleeding\u003C/strong\u003E does occur, the source in some 50 - 90% of cases will be from a diverticulum in the right colon and not related to an episode of acute diverticulitis. It typically presents as painless bright red blood per rectum due to erosion of vessels at the neck of the diverticulum. Bleeding as a complication of diverticulitis is very uncommon. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforation\u003C/strong\u003E is the second most common complication, which can lead to peritonitis if free perforation occurs. \u003Cstrong\u003EFistula development\u003C/strong\u003E can occur secondary to an inflammatory reaction between the colon and adjacent structures, most commonly the bladder. Stricture formation and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is a less common complication that may develop due to inflammatory stenosis or adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diverticulitis most commonly presents with lower abdominal pain.","Abscess formation, perforation and fistula formation are the well recognised potential complications of diverticulitis."],"references":["Piscopo N, Ellul P. Diverticular Disease: A Review on Pathophysiology and Recent Evidence. Ulster Med J. 2020 Sep;89(2):83-88. Epub 2020 Oct 21. PMID: 33093692; PMCID: PMC7576390","Feuerstein JD, Falchuk KR. Diverticulosis and Diverticulitis. Mayo Clin Proc. 2016 Aug;91(8):1094-104. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocp.2016.03.012. Epub 2016 May 5. PMID: 27156370","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Williams S, Bjarnason I, Hayee B, et al. Diverticular disease: update on pathophysiology, classification and\u00a0management. Frontline Gastroenterology 2024; 15:50\u201358."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15400"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21204"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21204"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/T1uD5Ld463d4MQ4FznSoHz0KsCljaA.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/T1uD5Ld463d4MQ4FznSoHz0KsCljaA.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":523,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:39:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:39:58+10:30"},"relationships"